ce and type/error checks.</description>\n    <location>/home/adam/.pi/agent/npm/node_modules/pi-lens/skills/lsp-navigation/SKILL.md</location>\n  </skill>\n  <skill>\n    <name>commit</name>\n    <description>Read this skill before making git commits</description>\n    <location>/home/adam/.pi/agent/git/github.com/tomsej/pi-ext/skills/commit/SKILL.md</location>\n  </skill>\n  <skill>\n    <name>github</name>\n    <description>Interact with GitHub using the `gh` CLI. Use `gh issue`, `gh pr`, `gh run`, and `gh api` for issues, PRs, CI runs, and advanced queries.</description>\n    <location>/home/adam/.pi/agent/git/github.com/tomsej/pi-ext/skills/github/SKILL.md</location>\n  </skill>\n  <skill>\n    <name>visit-webpage</name>\n    <description>Visit a webpage and extract its content as markdown, or fetch images. Use for reading articles, documentation, or any web page content. Handles both HTML pages (via Jina Reader) and image URLs (downloads and saves locally).</description>\n    <location>/home/adam/.pi/agent/git/github.com/tomsej/pi-ext/skills/visit-webpage/SKILL.md</location>\n  </skill>\n  <skill>\n    <name>sem</name>\n    <description>Entity-aware code change analysis using the pi-sem tools. Use when the user asks what changed, wants blast radius or affected tests, needs focused context for a function/class, wants review help on a commit/branch/PR, or asks to compare semantic diff with raw git diff. Prefer sem_context and sem_impact; use sem_diff selectively for summaries and reviews.</description>\n    <location>/home/adam/.pi/agent/git/github.com/tomsej/pi-ext/skills/sem/SKILL.md</location>\n  </skill>\n  <skill>\n    <name>librarian</name>\n    <description>Research open-source libraries with evidence-backed answers and GitHub permalinks. Use when the user asks about library internals, needs implementation details with source code references, wants to understand why something was changed, or needs authoritative answers backed by actual code. Excels at navigating large open-source repos and providing citations to exact lines of code.</description>\n    <location>/home/adam/.pi/agent/npm/node_modules/pi-web-access/skills/librarian/SKILL.md</location>\n  </skill>\n</available_skills>\nCurrent date: 2026-05-24\nCurrent working directory: /home/adam/projects/pi-agent-turn-limiter\n\n<wiki_status>LLM Wiki active — use wiki_recall for deeper search, wiki_retro to save new knowledge.</wiki_status>\n\n## Tool Guidance\n\n• Use the `read` tool for file contents (supports text and images).\n  - For large files, use `offset` and `limit` to read in chunks.\n• Execute commands with the `bash` tool. Use it for file operations like `ls`, `find`, `grep`.\n• Use the `edit` tool for precise text replacements in files. Match exact content including whitespace.\n• Use the `write` tool to create new files or overwrite existing ones completely.\n\nAvailable skills: archive-cleanup, backup, brainstorm, context-management, crash-proof, debugging-playbook, docker-ports, lessons-pipeline, pipeline-orchestration, planning-review, searxng, session-lessons-scan, stripe-v15, test-hygiene, vps-deploy, web-search, ast-grep, lsp-navigation, commit, github, visit-webpage, session-query, sem, librarian\nUse skill documentation for best practices on specific tools.\n<SESSION_MEMORY>\nYou have persistent memory across sessions via ~/.pi/agent/memory.md. Use /load-memory to read saved memories at the start of a new session and recall prior context.\n\nWhen pi's auto-compaction kicks in and summarises earlier context, that summary is stored in the session file. Use /save-session at the end of meaningful work sessions to persist those compaction summaries into ~/.pi/agent/memory.md for future sessions to recall.\n</SESSION_MEMORY>\n\n\n\n\n## Extension-Added Context\n\nThis prompt includes tool guidance and skill information loaded dynamically.\nIf you have additional requirements, configure them via --append-system-prompt or project context files.\n"
